{ The following opening repertoire is known as the "French Attack" and is a fun, aggressive, and offbeat repertoire that can be quite effective at the sub-master level. This repertoire is thoroughly covered in ChessMood's "BlackMood Openings" starter course. Visit chessmood.com/rosen to get free access through the end of June 2025. }
1. e4 e6 2. d4 (2. b3 d5 3. Bb2 { This gambit line known as the Horwitz Attack has been popularized by IM Levy Rozman (AKA GothamChess). See Chapter 7 for a simple recommendation to avoid white's trickery. }) 2... d5 3. e5 { The advanced variation } (3. Nc3 Nf6 4. e5 (4. Bg5 h6!? { a less common, but aggressive move that will leads to a pawn sacrifice. } 5. Bxf6 Qxf6 6. exd5 Bb4! { The McCutcheon Gambit! See chapter 5. }) 4... Ng8!? { The Kinder Surprise Variation! This rare line will take opponent's out of their opening preparation early and give black easy plans to pressure white's center. See Chapter 4 for more analysis. }) (3. exd5 exd5 { The French Exchange is one of the most common variation seen at the amateur level. While this symmetrical position maybe has a "dry" or "boring" reputation, it can be very fun if you know what to do. See chapter 2 for fun and aggressive strategies for black. }) 3... Bd7!? { An interesting sideline to try and trade off the bad French Bishop and avoid mainline opening theory. See Chapter 3 for more analysis. } *


[Event "How to play against 1.e4: A Simple, Fun, and Aggressive Opening Repertoire: Fighting the French Exchange"]
[Date "2025.06.16"]
