[ChapterName "Fighting the French Exchange"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/mr9g4cVe/fRDOKPNT"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/EricRosen"]
[UTCDate "2025.06.16"]
[UTCTime "03:51:25"]

1. e4 e6 2. d4 (2. c4 d5 3. cxd5 exd5 4. exd5 Nf6! { Black will eventually recapture on d5 with the knight and have very fluid development while playing against white's isolated d-pawn }) 2... d5 3. exd5 exd5 4. Nf3 (4. c4 { This move is not to be feared! Black will develop harmoniously and white will likely be left with an isolated d-pawn } 4... Nf6 5. Nf3 Bb4+ 6. Nc3 O-O 7. Be2 { This is our cue to now capture on c4 as white will lose a tempo moving the bishop again } 7... dxc4 8. Bxc4 Bg4 { Black has a pleasant position heading into the middlegame with pleasant piece harmony and positional pressure against white's isolated d-pawn } { [%csl Rd4][%cal Gb8d7,Gd7b6,Gc7c6,Gf8e8] }) 4... Nc6 { The following variation will demonstrate white's most common setup with kingside castling and black's optimal setup to create a sharp and attacking game. } 5. Be2 Bg4 6. O-O (6. h3 { Black is usually happy to see this move, as h3 will give black a target to attack in the middlegame. } 6... Bf5 7. O-O Bd6 8. c3 Nge7 9. Re1 Qd7 10. Nbd2 f6 11. Nf1 g5 { because white has committed to h3, the prospect of the g4 pawn break is even more powerful for black. } { [%cal Gh7h5,Gg5g4,Ge8c8] }) 6... Bd6 7. c3 Nge7 8. Re1 Qd7 9. Bg5?! { This natural developing move only gives black more time to expand on the kingside } (9. Nbd2 f6 10. Nf1 O-O-O 11. b4 Ng6 12. b5 Nce7 13. Qa4 Kb8 { [%cal Gh7h3] }) 9... f6 10. Bh4 g5 11. Bg3 Bxg3 12. hxg3 h5! { This position is way more fun to play as black! } { [%cal Gh5h4,Ge8c8,Ge7g6] } *


