1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nd2 Nc6!? { An off-beat variation that leads to some fun lines for black... } 4. Ngf3 (4. c3 e5! 5. dxe5 (5. exd5 Qxd5 { The queen can't easily be attacked as Bc4 allows Qxg2 }) 5... dxe4 6. Nxe4 Qxd1+ 7. Kxd1 Nxe5 $15) 4... Nf6 5. e5 (5. Bd3 Nb4 { [%csl Gd3][%cal Gb4d3] }) 5... Nd7 6. Be2 (6. Bd3 Nb4 { [%csl Gc5,Gd3][%cal Gc7c5,Gb4d3] }) 6... f6! { An important break -- there are now 3 attackers against white's e5-pawn and white is obliged to capture on f6. } { [%csl Re5][%cal Gf6e5,Gd7e5,Gc6e5] } 7. exf6 Qxf6 { The most active recapture } 8. c3 Bd6 { e5 is now pretty much unstoppable. } { [%csl Ge5][%cal Ge6e5] } 9. O-O e5 10. dxe5 Ndxe5 { Great harmony for the black pieces! } { [%csl Ge5,Gd6,Gc6,Gg8,Gf2][%cal Ge8g8,Gf8f2,Gc8g4] } *


